e from the Old English personal name  <i>Ealda</i> or Old English  <i>ald</i> ‘old’ + Old English  <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’."],"variants":[{"name":"Olner","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Oldnall  , with dissimilation of  <i>l-l</i> to  <i>l-r</i>."]},{"name":"Oldale","meanings":["1  English: locative name, probably from Wooldale (WR Yorks), which is recorded as  <i>Wulvedale</i> in 1307. The place-name derives from Old English  <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’ + Old English  <i>dæl</i> or Old Scandinavian  <i>dalr</i> ‘valley’. The local pronunciation of the place-name, with loss of initial  <i>w-</i>, is given as [u:dl] in   Place-Names of WR Yorks  .","2  English: locative name, occasionally from one or other of the many places in England named Old Hall, such as Old Hall in Rayne (Essex), which is recorded as  <i>Old Halle</i> in 1425–35, and probably derives from Middle English  <i>olde</i> ‘old’ +  <i>halle</i> ‘large residence, hall’ (Old English  <i>ald</i>,  <i>hall</i>).","3  English: perhaps a variant of   Oldnall  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":51,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Oldhall was born in 1404, in Houghton, Norfolk, England as the daughter of William Oldhall. She had at least 2 daughters with Sir William Lexham. She died in 1473, in her hometown, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1404–1473":"1404–1473","1390–1480":"1390–1480","1426–1485":"1426–1485","–1494":"–1494","–Male":"Surnud","1404":"1404","1426":"1426","11 June 1426":"11. juuni 1426","1455":"1455","1485":"1485","1473":"1473","1494":"1494","1480":"1480","1390":"1390","West Lexham, Norfolk, England":"West Lexham, Norfolk, England","Houghton, Norfolk, England":"Houghton, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1404–1473":"1404–1473","1390–1480":"1390–1480","1426–1485":"1426–1485","–1494":"–1494","–Male":"Kuollut","1404":"1404","1426":"1426","11 June 1426":"11. kesäkuuta 1426","1455":"1455","1485":"1485","1473":"1473","1494":"1494","1480":"1480","1390":"1390","West Lexham, Norfolk, England":"West Lexham, Norfolk, England","Houghton, Norfolk, England":"Houghton, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"1404–1473":"1404–1473","1390–1480":"1390–1480","1426–1485":"1426–1485",